*  This class uses the JDK's XPath implementation as the basis for
* On instantiation, a DOM is created of the filesystem metadata starting form the rootDirectory.
*  This DOM can then be queried using standard XML tools.
*  Whilst this approach has been relatively quick to implement, it is still tied to the limitations of XPath.
*  Future implementations of this class are likely to implement the FSPath language fully themselves wthout relying on XPath.

*  The FSPath interface defines the methods required to query a filesystem.
*  The query language is based on XPath.
*  The filesystem is represented as a DOM.
*  The root of the DOM is the root directory of the filesystem.
*  Each directory is represented as an element.
*  Each file is represented as an element.
*  Each element has a number of attributes which represent the metadata of the file or directory.
*  The filesystem is represented as a DOM for a number of reasons:

*
  • It is a standard way of representing data

*
  • It is a standard way of querying data

*
  • It is a standard way of transforming data

*
  • It is a standard way of serialising data

*
  • It is a standard way of validating data
